com.itko.lisaint.servlet

Class ServletIntegrator

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.itko.lisaint.Integrator
      • com.itko.lisaint.servlet.ServletIntegrator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class ServletIntegrator
extends Integrator
implements java.io.Serializable
    This is the Integrator sub-class that Servlet application developers will work directly with in providing test-enabled components for their Lisa test case execution. Caution: most users will never need the following, so skip it if you wish! However, support is provided for those cases where you want Lisa to tell you your own session ID. Here's how:
    • Lisa invokes your servlet with an HTTP header variable that this class uses to know that Lisa is "on". You can also use the URL parameter "lisa.int=on"
    • You provide a response to Lisa, and in doing so, this class has fetched the HttpSession id and reported that value. During your processing, you can call ServletIntegrator.setSessionId( String s ) to override that default value.
    • Lisa now adds an HTTP header field that has that same session ID you provided.
    • When you call getSessionId() on this Integrator, it will give you what Lisa sent
    For most servlet authors, there is no need for this. However, some applications will find it very useful. For example, if you put the session ID into your URLs, then Lisa will either need to explicitly parse those out and use the correct one, or you can use this mechanism to fetch the right one.

      • isLisaOn

        public static boolean isLisaOn(javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest req)
        This method figures out if Lisa Integrator support has been turned on. Integrator support is turned on by a special HTTP header variable or URL parameter being specified. Note that w/i a servlet session, once Lisa Integrator support has been requested, it will remain in a requested state for the life of the session.
        Parameters:
        req - the request for the current servlet invocation
        Returns:
        true if Lisa Integrator support has been requested

      • getServletIntegrator

        public static ServletIntegrator getServletIntegrator(javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest req)
        Servlet authors will need a handle to this persistent and auto-created object in order to report to Lisa. This is the only way you can get a handle to your Integrator on the server side. If the Integrator does not already exist for this session, it will be created.
        Parameters:
        req - - the servlet request for the currently running servlet
        Returns:
        the Integrator object for this servlet session, or null if Lisa Integrator support is not requested
